You can also use a `for` loop to just run a block of code N times using a **Range**.

A Range is written as `(START..END)`.

```rust
for number in (1..4) {
    println!("{}!", number);
}
```
*Note: Ranges in Rust are exclusive at the end, meaning (1..4) prints 1, 2, 3.*
